Introduction
------------

Forcepoint Threat Protection for Linux (Second Look) performs enterprise-scale 
Linux memory forensics.  It checks the integrity of the running kernel, 
processes, and executable code cached in memory on Linux systems.  It alerts
users to rootkits, malware, and other unknown or unauthorized software
in memory.  Due to its integrity-based approach, it is not reliant on
signatures or prior knowledge of specific threats.

The Forcepoint Threat Protection for Linux - App for Splunk is a set
of custom dashboards that enable users to monitor the state of their
deployment, including scan and alert activity, based on messages
emitted from scanning servers and ingested into Splunk Enterprise.
From the App one can drill down with a single click to full forensic
context in the Threat Protection for Linux web interface.

Configuration
-------------

If you create a custom index for Threat Protection for Linux messages,
update the "secondlook-index" macro in:

Settings -> Advanced Search -> Search Macros

